ciologists, and has been primarily theoretically driven. It addresses a highly contested and timely agenda, one in which colonial historians have made major interventions: the nature of colonial governance and autonomy of the colonial polity. This book focusing on colonialism and the Chinese society in Hong Kong in a pivotal period will generate meaningful discussions and heated debates on comparisons between ‘colonialism’ in different space and time: between Hong Kong and other former British colonies; and between colonial and post-colonial Hong Kong.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aElectronic surveillancezChinazHong KongxHistoryy20th century. 0aImperialism. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Colonialism & Post-Colonialism.2bisacsh  aBritish colonialism.  aHong Kong.  aSino-British relations.  adecolonisation.  agovernance.  apolitical activism.  apolitical culture.  apublic opinion.  astate-society relations.  asurveillance.1 aMok, Florence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2023 eBook-Packagez9783111206455oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615820840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526158208423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526158208/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPb2023